                      Commentary on global crisis                    An eminent American philosopher with a particular interest in ancient Greek and Roman philosophy, political philosophy and ethics, Martha Nussbaum (picture here), though not a lawyer, is currently Ernst Freund Distinguished Service Professor of Law and Ethics at the University of Chicago, a chair that includes appointments in the philosophy department, the Law School, and the Divinity School. She also holds Associate appointments in Classics and Political Science, is a member of the Committee on Southern Asian Studies, and a Board Member of the Human Rights Program. Earlier, she taught at Harvard and Brown where she held the rank of university professor. This evening, Dr Nussbaum will deliver the keynote speech at a panel discussion on The Crisis of Civilisations, that talks about multiple crises afflicting todays world of conflicts, terrorism and greed. Revisiting Tagores vision in his Crisis in Civilisation, it promises to provide adequate food for thought to a discerning audience. Other speakers: Sabyasachi Bhattacharya, Rudrangshu Mukherjee, Monoj Kumar Mukherjee and Partha Ghose. Entry limited to members and invited guests. Presented by The Bengal Club, in collaboration with Happenings and in association with The Telegraph.
    Event: A panel discussion on The Crisis of Civilisations When: Today; 6.30 pm - 8 pm Where: The Bengal Club		                    
